Summary of the data preprocessing step¶

  • There are 6559 rows with missing
  • There are two types of potential treatment strategy:
    • use the Latitude of the NA rows to find close match from rows with Comp Terr value (this could reduce some rows od missing Comp Terr vales)
    • For the rows with missing Comp Terr Value, we use Unknown at this point for data visualization
  • Currently the dataset only has 2018_individual but not 2018_sales, so the annual sales for each an accout needs to be calculated

Data Imputation Based on the Data Preprocessing Step Summaries¶

In [8]:
# Create a function for imputing the missing Comp Terr through Latitude Value Match
reference_rows = merged_df[(merged_df['Latitude'] > 0.00) & merged_df['Comp Terr'].notna()]
missing_comp_terr_rows = merged_df[(merged_df['Latitude'] > 0.00) & merged_df['Comp Terr'].isna()]


def find_closest_latitude(row, reference_df):
    latitude = row['Latitude']

    closest_row = reference_df.iloc[(reference_df['Latitude'] - latitude).abs().argsort()[:1]]
    return closest_row['Comp Terr'].values[0]  # Return the closest Comp Terr value

merged_df.loc[missing_comp_terr_rows.index, 'Comp Terr'] = missing_comp_terr_rows.apply(
    find_closest_latitude, reference_df=reference_rows, axis=1
)


print(f"Number of rows with missing 'Comp Terr' after imputation: {merged_df['Comp Terr'].isna().sum()}")

Texual Summaries of the Annual Sales Data¶

  • 2022 has the most sales within 2018-2024, however we need to take into consideration of two parts:

    • 2018 annual sales data is generated through the sum of monthly 2018 sales, so the value might not be as accurate as the annual sales from other years.
    • The sales data for year 2024 only take into accounts of the first two quarters, so the annual sales are expected to be greater (around) twice of this number
    • But based on the company's explination, the sales from last year seems to stalled, and if that is the case, is this graph an accurate representation of the company's annual sales revenue?

  • Based on the Territory specific sales visualization, there are a few takes:

    • There are a few territories where they generate greate precentage of annual sales: Western, Central, Southern, and Northeast

  • One of the problem is that the region has several categories that could allign, we might need to reduce the categories within the Company Terr veriable

  • Another problem is that there ar currently more than 5053 rows that we labeled "Unknown" due to missing the Company Terr value.

# Create a Quartly Graph for each year

quarterly_sales_columns = {
    '2018': ['2018_q1', '2018_q2', '2018_q3', '2018_q4'],
    '2019': ['2019_q1', '2019_q2', '2019_q3', '2019_q4'],
    '2020': ['2020_q1', '2020_q2', '2020_q3', '2020_q4'],
    '2021': ['2021_q1', '2021_q2', '2021_q3', '2021_q4'],
    '2022': ['2022_q1', '2022_q2', '2022_q3', '2022_q4'],
    '2023': ['2023_q1', '2023_q2', '2023_q3', '2023_q4'],
    '2024': ['2024_q1', '2024_q2']  # Adjust if you only have Q1 and Q2 for 2024
}

# Loop through each year and plot the quarterly sales
for year, quarters in quarterly_sales_columns.items():
    if all(col in merged_df.columns for col in quarters):
        quarterly_sales = merged_df[quarters].sum()
        
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
        bars = plt.bar(quarters, quarterly_sales, color='skyblue')
        plt.title(f'Quarterly Sales Overview for {year}')
        plt.xlabel('Quarter')
        plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.grid(True)

        for bar, sales_value in zip(bars, quarterly_sales):
            plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_height() + 5000, 
                f'{sales_value:.0f}', ha='center', va='bottom', color='blue')

        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

# Direct comparison of each year's quartly sales data
quarterly_sales_columns = {
    'Q1': ['2018_q1', '2019_q1', '2020_q1', '2021_q1', '2022_q1', '2023_q1', '2024_q1'],
    'Q2': ['2018_q2', '2019_q2', '2020_q2', '2021_q2', '2022_q2', '2023_q2', '2024_q2'],
    'Q3': ['2018_q3', '2019_q3', '2020_q3', '2021_q3', '2022_q3', '2023_q3'],  
    'Q4': ['2018_q4', '2019_q4', '2020_q4', '2021_q4', '2022_q4', '2023_q4'] 
}


years = ['2018', '2019', '2020', '2021', '2022', '2023', '2024']
quarters = ['Q1', 'Q2', 'Q3', 'Q4']
x = np.arange(len(quarters))  
width = 0.1  

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

for i, year in enumerate(years):
    sales_data = []
    for quarter in quarterly_sales_columns:
        column_name = f'{year.lower()}_{quarter.lower()}'
        if column_name in merged_df.columns:
            sales_data.append(merged_df[column_name].sum())
        else:
            sales_data.append(0)

    x_positions = x + i * width
    
    plt.bar(x_positions, sales_data, width=width, label=year)


plt.title('Quarterly Sales Comparison Across Years (2018-2024)', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Quarter')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.xticks(x + width * (len(years) / 2), quarters)
plt.legend(title='Year', loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True)


plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Monthly Sales Data by year, whith the regional sales contribution to each month's sales

#Define the monthly sales columns for each year
monthly_sales_columns = {
    '2018': [f'2018_{str(month).zfill(2)}' for month in range(1, 13)],
    '2019': [f'2019_{str(month).zfill(2)}' for month in range(1, 13)],
    '2020': [f'2020_{str(month).zfill(2)}' for month in range(1, 13)],
    '2021': [f'2021_{str(month).zfill(2)}' for month in range(1, 13)],
    '2022': [f'2022_{str(month).zfill(2)}' for month in range(1, 13)],
    '2023': [f'2023_{str(month).zfill(2)}' for month in range(1, 13)],
    '2024': [f'2024_{str(month).zfill(2)}' for month in range(1, 9)] 
}


for year, months in monthly_sales_columns.items():
    if all(col in merged_df.columns for col in months):
        region_monthly_sales = merged_df.groupby('Comp Terr')[months].sum()


        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
        bars = region_monthly_sales.T.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(12, 8), ax=plt.gca())

        total_monthly_sales = region_monthly_sales.sum(axis=0)

        for idx, sales_value in enumerate(total_monthly_sales):
            plt.text(idx, sales_value + 1000,  
                     f'{sales_value:.0f}', ha='center', va='bottom', color='black')

        plt.title(f'Monthly Sales by Region in {year}')
        plt.xlabel('Month')
        plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.legend(title='Region', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left') 
        plt.grid(True)


        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

annual_sales_columns = {
    '2018': '2018_sales',
    '2019': '2019_sales',
    '2020': '2020_sales',
    '2021': '2021_sales',
    '2022': '2022_sales',
    '2023': '2023_sales',
    '2024': '2024_sales'
}

clients_with_sales = []


for year, sales_column in annual_sales_columns.items():
    if sales_column in merged_df.columns:
        non_zero_sales_count = merged_df[merged_df[sales_column] > 0]['composite_key'].nunique()
        clients_with_sales.append(non_zero_sales_count)
    else:
        clients_with_sales.append(0)

years = list(annual_sales_columns.keys())

             f'{count}', ha='center', va='bottom', color='black')

Create a graph to show the Average Annual Sales by Number of CLients with Sales¶

In [71]:
annual_sales_columns = {
    '2018': '2018_sales',
    '2019': '2019_sales',
    '2020': '2020_sales',
    '2021': '2021_sales',
    '2022': '2022_sales',
    '2023': '2023_sales',
    '2024': '2024_sales'
}

total_sales_per_year = []
clients_with_sales_per_year = []
average_sales_per_client = []

for year, sales_column in annual_sales_columns.items():
    if sales_column in merged_df.columns:
        total_sales = merged_df[sales_column].sum()
        total_sales_per_year.append(total_sales)

        non_zero_sales_count = merged_df[merged_df[sales_column] > 0]['composite_key'].nunique()
        clients_with_sales_per_year.append(non_zero_sales_count)

        if non_zero_sales_count > 0:
            average_sales = total_sales / non_zero_sales_count
        else:
            average_sales = 0
        average_sales_per_client.append(average_sales)
    else:
        total_sales_per_year.append(0)
        clients_with_sales_per_year.append(0)
        average_sales_per_client.append(0)

years = list(annual_sales_columns.keys())

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
bars = plt.bar(years, average_sales_per_client, color='lightgreen')

for bar, avg_sales in zip(bars, average_sales_per_client):
    plt.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_height() + 2000, 
             f'{avg_sales:.2f}', ha='center', va='bottom', color='black')

plt.title('Annual Average Sales per Client (2018-2024)')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Average Sales per Client')
plt.grid(axis='y')


plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

annual_sales_columns = {
    '2018': '2018_sales',
    '2019': '2019_sales',
    '2020': '2020_sales',
    '2021': '2021_sales',
    '2022': '2022_sales',

top_clients = {}
